===Flag===
[[File:Medal of Honor Flag with Gold Fringe.svg|thumb|Medal of Honor Flag]]
On October 23, 2002, {{USPL|107|248}} was enacted, modifying {{UnitedStatesCode|36|903}}, authorizing a Medal of Honor flag to be presented to recipients of the decoration.<ref name="flaglaw">{{cite web|year = 23 Oct 2002 |url = http://uscode.house.gov/download/pls/36C9.txt |title = Designation of the Medal of Honor Flag |publisher = US Code.gov |accessdate = 2006-07-23}}</ref>

The flag was based on a concept by retired [[U.S. Army Special Forces|Army Special Forces]] First Sergeant Bill Kendall of [[Jefferson, Iowa]],<ref name="Kendall">{{cite web|url = http://www4.army.mil/news/article.php?story=7244|title = Special Forces veteran's idea leads to new Medal of Honor flag |publisher = Army News Service|accessdate = 2006-07-24|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060111151709/http://www4.army.mil/news/article.php?story=7244 |archivedate = January 11, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref> who designed a flag to honor Medal of Honor recipient Captain [[Darrell Lindsey]], a [[B-26 Marauder|B-26]] pilot killed in World War II who was from Jefferson. Kendall's design of a light blue field emblazoned with 13 white five-pointed stars was nearly identical to that of Sarah LeClerc's of the [[U.S. Army Institute of Heraldry|Institute of Heraldry]]. LeClerc's design, ultimately accepted as the official flag, does not include the words "Medal of Honor" and is fringed in gold. The color of the field and the 13 white stars, arranged in the form of a three bar [[Chevron (insignia)|chevron]], consisting of two chevrons of five stars and one chevron of three stars,<ref name="regulations"/> replicate the Medal of Honor ribbon. The flag has no set proportions.<ref name="flag">{{cite web|url = http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Flags_Guidons/MedalOfHonorFlag.htm |title = Medal of Honor Flag |work = The Institute of Heraldry |publisher = US Army |accessdate = 2006-07-21| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060911012812/http://www.tioh.hqda.pentagon.mil/Flags_Guidons/MedalOfHonorFlag.htm| archivedate = September 11, 2006}}</ref>

The first Medal of Honor recipient to receive the official flag was Sergeant First Class [[Paul R. Smith]]. The flag was cased and presented to his family along with his medal.<ref name="smithflag">{{cite web|last = Cramer |first = Eric W. |date = March 29, 2005 |url = http://www4.army.mil/ocpa/read.php?story_id_key=7085 |title = First Medal of Honor flag to be presented |work = Army News Service |publisher = US Army|accessdate = 2006-07-21|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060721040551/http://www4.army.mil/ocpa/read.php?story_id_key=7085 |archivedate = July 21, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref> A special ceremony presenting this flag to 60 Medal of Honor recipients was held onboard {{USS|Constitution}} on September 30, 2006.<ref name="flagpresent">{{cite web|year = 2006 |url = http://www.news.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=25834 |title = "Old Ironsides" Hosts Medal of Honor Recipients |work = Navy Newsstand |publisher = US Navy |accessdate = 2006-10-01}}</ref>

==Presenting==
[[File:Henry Breault2.jpg|right|thumb|President [[Calvin Coolidge]] bestowing the Medal of Honor upon [[Henry Breault]], March 8, 1924]]
There are two distinct protocols for awarding the Medal of Honor. The first and most common is nomination and approval through a service member's [[chain of command]]. The second method is nomination by a member of [[United States Congress|Congress]] (generally at the request of a constituent) and approval by a special [[act of Congress]]. In both cases, the Medal of Honor is presented by the President on behalf of and in the name of the Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh.html |title=Medal of Honor Citations |publisher=History.army.mil |date=2008-06-04 |accessdate=2012-01-03}}</ref>

===Evolution of criteria===
Several months after President Abraham Lincoln signed Public Resolution 82 into law on December 21, 1861, a similar resolution for the Army was passed. Six [[Union Army|Union]] soldiers who [[Great Locomotive Chase|hijacked the ''General'']], a [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] [[locomotive]] were the first recipients.<ref name="MWxvii">{{harvnb|Mikaelian|Wallace|2003|p=xvii}}</ref> Raid leader [[James J. Andrews]], a civilian hanged as a Union spy, did not receive the medal. Many Medals of Honor awarded in the 19th century were associated with saving the flag, not just for patriotic reasons, but because the flag was a primary means of battlefield communication. During the time of the Civil War, no other military award was authorized, and to many this explains why some seemingly less notable actions were recognized by the Medal of Honor during that war. The criteria for the award tightened after [[World War I]] and starting in 1942, the medal would be awarded only for action in combat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/faqs/faq38-1.htm|title=The Navy's Medal of Honor|accessdate=2012-01-26|publisher=US Navy}}</ref>

Early in the 20th century, the Navy awarded many Medals of Honor for peacetime bravery. For instance, seven sailors aboard the {{USS|Iowa|BB-4}} received the medal when a boiler exploded on January 25, 1904. Aboard the {{USS|Chicago|CA-14}} in 1901, [[John Henry Helms]] received the medal for saving the ship's cook from drowning. Even after World War I, [[Richard Evelyn Byrd|Richard Byrd]] and [[Floyd Bennett]] received the medal for exploration of the [[North Pole]].<ref name="HargisSinton2003">{{cite book|last1=argis|first1=Robert H|last2=Sinton|first2=Starr |title=World War II Medal of Honor recipients (1): Navy & USMC|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JdGr1QFy9HwC&pg=PA6|accessdate=2012-03-14|year=2003|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84176-613-3|page=6}}</ref>  [[Thomas J. Ryan (admiral)|Thomas J. Ryan]] received it for saving a woman from the burning Grand Hotel in [[Yokohama]], Japan, following the 1923 [[Great Kant<U+014D> earthquake]].<ref name="ryan">{{cite web|url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/interim1920-40.html |title = Medal of Honor Recipients, Interim Awards 1920<U+2013>1940 |publisher = [[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate = 2006-07-23}}</ref>

Between 1919 and 1942, the Navy issued two separate versions of the Medal of Honor, one for non-combat bravery and the other for combat-related acts. Official accounts vary, but generally the combat Medal of Honor was known as the Tiffany Cross, after the company that [[Tiffany & Co.|designed the medal]]. The Tiffany Cross was first awarded in 1919, but was unpopular, partly because of its design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=7048|title="Tiffany" Medal of Honor Comes to Navy Museum|date=2003-04-27|last=Birnie|first=Michael|publisher=United States Navy|work=[[U.S. Navy Museum]]|accessdate=2010-02-15}}</ref> There were two awards of the Tiffany Cross Medal of Honor for non-combat to Commander, later Rear Admiral Richard Byrd and Floyd Bennett for their flight over the North Pole in 1926, as authorized by a special act of congress.
<ref>{{Cite book|title=Above and Beyond: The Aviation Medals of Honor |first=Barrett |last=Tillman |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |location=Washington, D.C. |year=2003 |page=3}}</ref> As a result, in 1942, the United States Navy reverted to a single Medal of Honor, awarded only for heroism.<ref name="typessecnav"/>
Since the beginning of World War II, the medal has been awarded for extreme bravery beyond the call of duty while engaged in action against an enemy. Arising from these criteria, approximately 60 percent of the medals earned during and after World War II have been awarded posthumously.<ref name="mohstats">{{cite web|month = May | year = 2003 |url = http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/mohstats.html |title = Medal of Honor Statistics |publisher = [[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate = 2006-07-23}}</ref> Capt. [[William McGonagle]] is an exception to the enemy action rule, receiving his medal for his actions during the [[USS Liberty incident|USS ''Liberty'' incident]].<ref name="Liberty1">{{cite web|month = July | year = 2003 |url = http://www.nsa.gov/liberty/ |title = USS Liberty |publisher = National Security Agency, Central Security Service |accessdate = July 23, 2006|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060721005215/http://www.nsa.gov/liberty/ |archivedate = July 21, 2006|deadurl=yes}} audio and transcripts</ref><ref name="Liberty2">{{cite web|url = http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/sh-usn/usnsh-l/agtr5.htm |title = USS Liberty |publisher = Naval Historical Center |accessdate = 2006-07-23}} audio and transcripts</ref>

==Authority and privileges==
[[File:C-Chatanooga Cemetery2.jpg|220px|thumb|Monument and graves, at the [[Chattanooga National Cemetery]] in Tennessee, of the Civil War Medal of Honor recipients in Andrew's Raid]][[File:Jimmie W. Monteith Jr. Gravemarker 03.jpg|thumb|right|The grave of a recipient at the [[Normandy American Cemetery and Memorial]]]]
[[File:James H Robinson grave.jpg|thumb|Grave of a recipient at the [[Memphis National Cemetery]]]]

The U.S. Army Medal of Honor was first authorized by a joint resolution of Congress on July 12, 1862.<ref>{{cite video
 | title =Big Picture: Hall of Heroes
 | url =http://www.archive.org/details/gov.archives.arc.2569905
 | publisher =U.S. Army Audiovisual Center.
 |accessdate=2012-03-14
}}</ref> The specific authorizing statute was {{UnitedStatesCode|10|3741}}, which states:

{{quote|The President may award, and present in the name of Congress, a medal of honor of appropriate design, with ribbons and appurtenances, to a person who while a member of the Army, distinguished himself conspicuously by gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of his life above and beyond the call of duty.<ref name="1998code">{{cite web|date = January 26, 1998 |url = http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/uscode10/usc_sec_10_00003741----000-.html |title = Sec. 3741. Medal of honor: award |publisher =Cornell University |accessdate = 2012-01-26}}</ref>}}

Later authorizations created similar medals for other branches of the service.

===Privileges and courtesies===
The Medal of Honor confers special privileges on its recipients. By law, recipients have several benefits:<ref name="benefits">{{cite web|url = http://www.tricare.osd.mil/medalofhonor/default.cfm |title = Medal of Honor Recipients |publisher = Tricare |accessdate = 2006-07-24}}</ref><ref name="benefits3">{{cite web|url = http://www.vba.va.gov/bln/21/Rates/special1.htm |title = Special Benefits and Allowances Table |publisher = Dept. of Veterans Affairs |accessdate = 2006-07-24}}</ref>
* Each Medal of Honor recipient may have his or her name entered on the Medal of Honor Roll ({{UnitedStatesCode|38|1560}}). Each person whose name is placed on the Medal of Honor Roll is certified to the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] as being entitled to receive a monthly pension above and beyond any military pensions or other benefits for which they may be eligible. The pension is subject to [[Cost of living#Other uses of the term "cost-of-living allowance"|cost-of-living increases]]; as of 2011, it is $1,237 a month.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.vba.va.gov/bln/21/Rates/special1.htm|title = Department of Veterans Affairs Special Allowances for Clothing, Automobiles, and Medal of Honor Pension}}</ref>
* Enlisted recipients of the Medal of Honor are entitled to a supplemental uniform allowance.
* Recipients receive special entitlements to air transportation under the provisions of DOD Regulation 4515.13-R.
* Special identification cards and commissary and exchange privileges are provided for Medal of Honor recipients and their eligible dependents.
* Eligibility for interment at [[Arlington National Cemetery]] if not otherwise eligible.<ref>32 CFR 553.15(d)(1)</ref>
* Fully qualified children of recipients are eligible for admission to the [[List of United States military schools and academies|United States military academies]] without regard to the nomination and quota requirements.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://webster-new.dmz.usna.edu/Admissions/stnommed.htm|title = USNA. Admissions}}</ref>
* Recipients receive a 10 percent increase in retired pay under {{UnitedStatesCode|10|3991}}.
* Those awarded the medal after October 23, 2002, receive a Medal of Honor Flag. The law specified that all 103 living prior recipients as of that date would receive a flag. ({{UnitedStatesCode|14|505}}).
* Recipients receive an invitation to all future [[United States presidential inauguration|presidential inaugurations]] and [[United States presidential inaugural balls|inaugural balls]].<ref name="cnnGiunta">{{cite news| url= http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/02/08/army.medal/ | title= America's newest Medal of Honor recipient is leaving the Army | date= February 8, 2011 | publisher=CNN | accessdate= 2011-02-09| first=Larry| last= Shaughnessy| quote= Even though he's leaving the Army, Giunta is entitled to a number of special benefits reserved for Medal of Honor recipients, including a monthly Veterans Affairs pension of more than $1,237 a month for life as well as an invitation to every presidential inauguration and inauguration party.}}</ref>
* As with all medals, retired personnel may wear the Medal of Honor on "appropriate" civilian clothing. Regulations specify that recipients of the Medal of Honor are allowed to wear the uniform "at their pleasure" with standard restrictions on political, commercial, or extremist purposes; other former members of the armed forces may do so only at certain ceremonial occasions.<ref name="AR670">{{cite web|url = http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/r670_1.pdf|format=PDF|title = Wear and Appearance of Army Uniforms and Insignia |page= 316 |publisher = Department of the Army |accessdate = 2011-09-21}}</ref>
* Many states offer distinctive Medal of Honor vehicle [[Vehicle registration plates of the United States|license plates]] to recipients without additional charges or fees.<ref>{{cite web|title=Veteran & Military Service-related License Plates|url=http://www.oregon.gov/ODOT/DMV/vehicle/platevet.shtml|publisher=Oregon DMV|accessdate= 2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Military License Plates|url=http://www.flhsmv.gov/specialtytags/miltags.html#mh|publisher=Florida Department of Highway Safety & Motor Vehicles|accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Veterans & Military Plates |url=http://www.dmvnv.com/platesveterans.htm|publisher=Nevada DMV|accessdate= 2011-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Medal of Honor license plates|url=http://www.dot.wisconsin.gov/drivers/vehicles/personal/special/moh.htm|publisher=Wisconsin Department of Transportation|accessdate=14 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Special Recognition License Plates|url=http://www.dmv.ca.gov/pubs/plates/specialrecogplates.htm|publisher=California DMV|accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Medal of Honor Plates|url=http://www.iowadot.gov/mvd/ovs/plates/honor.htm|publisher=Iown Department of Transportation|accessdate= 2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Military personnel|url=http://www.state.nj.us/mvc/Vehicle/MilitaryPersonnel.htm|publisher=State of New Jersey, Motor Vehicle Commission|accessdate= 2011-09-19}}</ref>

===Saluting===
* Although not required by law or military regulation,<ref>United States Army. ''[http://www.hqusareur.army.mil/NCOoutlook/Documents/FM%207-21.13.pdf Field Manual 7-21.13 The Soldier's Guide'']. 2003. Chapter 4.</ref> members of the [[Uniformed services of the United States|uniformed services]] are encouraged to render salutes to recipients of the Medal of Honor as a matter of respect and courtesy regardless of rank or status.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uscg.mil/auxiliary/cginfo/uniforms/custom.asp |title=USCG CG-5421 Web Site - Customs & Courtesy |publisher=Uscg.mil |date=2011-02-18 |accessdate=2012-01-03}}</ref>

==Legal protection==
Until late 2006, the Medal of Honor was the only service decoration afforded special protection under federal law to prevent it from being imitated or privately sold. The [[Stolen Valor Act of 2005]], enacted December 20, 2006 but later ruled to be unconstitutional, extended federal protection to include false verbal, written, or physical claims to other military decorations, service medals, or military badges to which a person is not entitled.<ref name="s1998track">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=s109-1998 |title=S. 1998: Stolen Valor Act of 2005 |work=109th U.S. Congress (2005<U+2013>2006) |publisher=GovTrak.us |accessdate=2007-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{usc|18|704}}</ref> In [[United States v. Alvarez]], the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|9th Circuit Court of Appeals]] ruled in 2010 that the Stolen Valor Act was unconstitutional.  In a 2-1 decision, it stated that the Act was a violation of [[free speech]] because it did not fall within one of the previously announced exceptions to free speech, and the speech it proscribed was, therefore, [[protected speech]].  The Court went on to find that while the driving purpose of the law was compelling, the law was not narrowly tailored to meet that purpose.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/aug/18/appeals-court-stolen-valor-act-unconstitutional/ |title=Appeals court: Stolen Valor Act unconstitutional |date=August 18, 2010 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Washington Times |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref> On February 22, 2012, the Supreme Court heard arguments in an appeal of the 9th Circuit's decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/argument_transcripts/11-210.pdf|title=IN THE SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES, UNITED STATES v. XAVIER ALVAREZ No. 11-210|format=pdf|date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=2012-05-12}}</ref>

[[File:Moh2.jpg|right|thumb|The Medal of Honor on display]]
The [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] issues all Medals of Honor to recipients in the original only. A duplicate medal (marked as such) may be issued, free of charge, to replace a lost, destroyed or stolen one upon written application, subject to approval of the service secretary. Misuse of the medal, including unauthorized manufacture or wear, is punishable by a fine up to $100,000 and imprisonment up to one year pursuant to {{uscsub|18|704|b}}. After the Army redesigned its medal in 1903, a [[patent]] was issued<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/patents?q=D37236 |title=D37236 - Google Patents |publisher=Google.com |date=1904-11-22 |accessdate=2011-10-30}}</ref> to legally prevent others from making the medal. When the patent expired, the Federal government enacted a law making it illegal to produce, wear, or distribute the Medal of Honor without proper authority. A number of veterans' organizations and private companies devote themselves to exposing those who falsely claim to have received the Medal of Honor.<ref name="phony">{{Cite news|last = Chozick |first = Amy |url = http://online.wsj.com/public/article/SB111533986173926430-K_XMqM2Fe4Gn2S_wmni1njavo2k_20060505.html?mod=blogs |title = Veterans' Web Sites Expose Pseudo Heroes, Phony Honors |publisher = Wall Street Journal |accessdate = 2006-07-20 | date=2005-05-06}}</ref>

===Enforcement===
HLI Lordship Industries Inc., a former Medal of Honor contractor, was fined in 1996 for selling 300 medals for US $75 each.<ref name="hli2">{{Cite news|date = December 4, 1996 |url = http://www.cnn.com/US/9612/04/briefs/medal.html |title = Company fined for selling fake Medals of Honor |work = US News |publisher = CNN |accessdate = 2006-07-21|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060203042609/http://www.cnn.com/US/9612/04/briefs/medal.html |archivedate = February 3, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

In that year, Fort Lauderdale, Florida, resident Jackie Stern was convicted of wearing a medal to which he was not entitled; instead of six months in jail, a federal judge sentenced him to serve one year's probation and to write a letter of apology to each of the then living 171 recipients of the medal; the letter was published in the local newspaper.<ref name="stern">{{Cite news|date = December 4, 1996 |url = http://www.cnn.com/US/9612/04/medal.without.honor/ |title = Florida Man wears medal without Honor |work = US News |publisher = CNN |accessdate = 2006-09-30}}</ref>

In 2003, Edward Fedora and Gisela Fedora were charged with violating {{uscsub|18|704|b}}, ''Unlawful Sale of a Medal of Honor'', for selling medals awarded to U.S. Navy Sailor [[Robert Blume]] (for action in the [[Spanish-American War]]) and to U.S. Army First Sergeant George Washington Roosevelt (for action in the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]) to an [[FBI]] agent.<ref name="blume">{{cite web|date = July 9, 2003 |url = http://www.fbi.gov/pressrel/pressrel03/metal070903.htm |title = Defendants Charged With Conspiracy to Sell Several Congressional Medals of Honor |publisher = Federal Bureau of Investigation |accessdate = 2006-07-23 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060720022357/http://www.fbi.gov/pressrel/pressrel03/metal070903.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-07-20}}</ref> Edward Fedora pleaded guilty and was sentenced to prison.<ref name="edward">{{cite web|date = May 28, 2004 |url = http://www.fbi.gov/page2/may04/052804medal.htm |title = Honoring Our Veterans |publisher = Federal Bureau of Investigation |accessdate = 2006-07-23}}</ref>

==Recipients==
{{Main|List of Medal of Honor recipients}}
As of 2006, 3,475 medals have been awarded to 3,456 different people.<ref name="mohshistory">{{cite web|url = http://www.cmohs.org/society-history.php |title = The Congressional Medal of Honor Society's History |work = Official Site |publisher = Congressional Medal of Honor Society |accessdate = 2012-03-14}}</ref><ref name="usmcmoh">{{cite web|url = http://www.usmc.mil/moh.nsf/ |title = Marines Awarded the Medal of Honor |publisher = US Marine Corps |accessdate = 2006-07-20|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060727232259/http://www.usmc.mil/moh.nsf/ |archivedate = July 27, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Nineteen men received a second award: 14 of these received two separate medals for two separate actions, and five received both the Navy and the Army Medals of Honor for the same action. For actions since the beginning of World War II, 861 Medals of Honor have been awarded, 530 (or 62%) posthumously. In total, 627 of the medals have been awarded posthumously.<ref name="mohstats"/>

The first Army Medal of Honor was awarded to Private [[Jacob Parrott]] during the American Civil War for his role in the [[Andrews Raid]].<ref name="MWxviii"/> The only female Medal of Honor recipient is [[Mary Edwards Walker]], a Civil War surgeon. Her medal was rescinded in 1917 along with many other non-combat awards, but it was restored by President [[Jimmy Carter]] in 1977 (see Evolution of Criteria, above).<ref name="walker">{{harvnb|Mikaelian|Wallace|2003|p=8}}</ref>

While current regulations, ({{UnitedStatesCode|10|6241}}), beginning in 1918, explicitly state that recipients must be serving in the U.S. Armed Forces at the time of performing a valorous act that warrants the award, exceptions have been made. For example, [[Charles Lindbergh]], while a reserve member of the [[U.S. Army Air Corps]], received his Medal of Honor as a civilian pilot.<ref name="HargisSinton2003"/> In addition, the Medal of Honor was presented to the [[The Unknown Warrior|British Unknown Warrior]] by [[John J. Pershing|General Pershing]] on October 17, 1921. On November 11, 1921, the [[Tomb of the Unknowns|U.S. Unknown Soldier]] was reciprocally awarded the [[Victoria Cross]], the British military's highest award for valor. Apart from these few exceptions, Medals of Honor can be awarded only to members of the U.S. armed forces<U+2014>although being a U.S. citizen is not a prerequisite. Sixty-one [[Canada|Canadians]] who were serving in the United States armed forces have been awarded the Medal of Honor, with a majority awarded for actions in the American Civil War. Since 1900, only four have been awarded to Canadians.<ref name="cbc">{{Cite news|date = July 1, 2005 |url = http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2005/07/01/canadians-usmedal050701.html |title = Canada honours winners of top U.S. medal |publisher = CBC News|accessdate = 2006-07-20|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070529190113/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2005/07/01/canadians-usmedal050701.html |archivedate = May 29, 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> In the Vietnam War, [[Peter C. Lemon]] was the only Canadian recipient of the Medal of Honor.<ref name="vwam">{{Cite news|url = http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2005/07/01/canadians-usmedal050701.html |title = Thousands of Canadians, including a Medal of Honor winner, served with the U.S. military in Vietnam |publisher = Veterans With a Mission |accessdate = 2006-07-20|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070529190113/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2005/07/01/canadians-usmedal050701.html |archivedate = May 29, 2007|deadurl=yes | date=2005-07-01}}</ref>

