As of 2010, the largest collective group in the U.S. armed services awarded the Medal of Honor with 22&nbsp;medals are [[United States Navy Hospital Corpsman#Hospital Corpsmen who received the Medal of Honor|United States Navy Hospital Corpsmen.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pacom.mil/web/Site_Pages/Media/News%20201006/20100617-Yokosuka%20112th%20Hpospital%20B_Day.shtml |title=USPACOM - United States Pacific Command |publisher=Pacom.mil |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2012-01-03}}</ref>

===Double recipients===
Nineteen men have been awarded the Medal of Honor twice. Five of these men were awarded both the Army and Navy Medal of Honor for the same action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/mohstats.html |title=Medal of Honor Statistics |publisher=History.army.mil |date= |accessdate=2012-05-12}}</ref> Since February 1919, no single individual can be awarded more than one Medal of Honor for the same action although a member of one branch of the armed forces can receive the Medal of Honor from another branch, if the actions for which it was awarded were under the authority of the said branch.<ref>{{cite book|title=1919 Supplement to United States Complied Statutes, 1918|date=1919|publisher=West Publishing Company |pages=30,49|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=A9MZAAAAYAAJ&dq|accessdate=2012-05-12}}</ref> The maximum number of Medals of Honor earned by any service member has been two.<ref name=navyfaq/>

